According to Article 68 of the EU AI Act, the scientific panel of independent experts is established to support the enforcement activities under this Regulation. The specific roles and responsibilities assigned to the scientific panel are as follows:

1. The Commission shall make provisions on the establishment of the scientific panel by means of an implementing act adopted in accordance with the examination procedure referred to in Article 98(2).

2. The scientific panel shall consist of experts selected by the Commission on the basis of up-to-date scientific or technical expertise in the field of AI necessary for the tasks set out in paragraph 3.

3. The scientific panel shall advise and support the AI Office, in particular with regard to the following tasks:

(a) Supporting the implementation and enforcement of this Regulation as regards general-purpose AI models and systems, in particular by:

(i) Alerting the AI Office of possible systemic risks at Union level of general-purpose AI models, in accordance with Article 90;

(ii) Contributing to the development of tools and methodologies for evaluating capabilities of general-purpose AI models and systems, including through benchmarks;

(iii) Providing advice on the classification of general-purpose AI models with systemic risk;

(iv) Providing advice on the classification of various general-purpose AI models and systems;

(v) Contributing to the development of tools and templates;

(b) Supporting the work of market surveillance authorities, at their request;

(c) Supporting cross-border market surveillance activities as referred to in Article 74(11), without prejudice to the powers of market surveillance authorities;

(d) Supporting the AI Office in carrying out its duties in the context of the Union safeguard procedure pursuant to Article 81.

4. The experts on the scientific panel shall perform their tasks with impartiality and objectivity, and shall ensure the confidentiality of information and data obtained in carrying out their tasks and activities.

5. The implementing act referred to in paragraph 1 shall include provisions on the conditions, procedures, and detailed arrangements for the scientific panel and its members to issue alerts and to request the assistance of the AI Office for the performance of the tasks of the scientific panel.

According to Article 59 of the EU AI Act, personal data lawfully collected for other purposes may be processed solely for the purpose of developing, training, and testing certain AI systems in the sandbox when the following conditions are met:

1. The AI systems shall be developed for safeguarding substantial public interest by a public authority or another natural or legal person and in one or more of the following areas:
   (a) public safety and public health, including disease detection, diagnosis prevention, control and treatment and improvement of health care systems;
   (b) a high level of protection and improvement of the quality of the environment, protection of biodiversity, protection against pollution, green transition measures, climate change mitigation and adaptation measures;
   (c) energy sustainability;
   (d) safety and resilience of transport systems and mobility, critical infrastructure and networks;
   (e) efficiency and quality of public administration and public services.

2. The data processed are necessary for complying with one or more of the requirements referred to in Chapter III, Section 2 where those requirements cannot effectively be fulfilled by processing anonymised, synthetic or other non-personal data.

3. There are effective monitoring mechanisms to identify if any high risks to the rights and freedoms of the data subjects, as referred to in Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and in Article 39 of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, may arise during the sandbox experimentation, as well as response mechanisms to promptly mitigate those risks and, where necessary, stop the processing.

4. Any personal data to be processed in the context of the sandbox are in a functionally separate, isolated and protected data processing environment under the control of the prospective provider, and only authorized persons have access to those data.

According to Article 59 of the EU AI Act, personal data lawfully collected for other purposes may be processed solely for the purpose of developing, training, and testing certain AI systems in the sandbox when the following conditions are met:

(a) AI systems shall be developed for safeguarding substantial public interest by a public authority or another natural or legal person and in one or more of the following areas:
(i) public safety and public health, including disease detection, diagnosis prevention, control and treatment and improvement of health care systems;
(ii) a high level of protection and improvement of the quality of the environment, protection of biodiversity, protection against pollution, green transition measures, climate change mitigation and adaptation measures;
(iii) energy sustainability;
(iv) safety and resilience of transport systems and mobility, critical infrastructure and networks;
(v) efficiency and quality of public administration and public services;

(b) the data processed are necessary for complying with one or more of the requirements referred to in Chapter III, Section 2 where those requirements cannot effectively be fulfilled by processing anonymised, synthetic or other non-personal data;

(c) there are effective monitoring mechanisms to identify if any high risks to the rights and freedoms of the data subjects, as referred to in Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and in Article 39 of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, may arise during the sandbox experimentation, as well as response mechanisms to promptly mitigate those risks and, where necessary, stop the processing;

(d) any personal data to be processed in the context of the sandbox are in a functionally separate, isolated and protected data processing environment under the control of the prospective provider, and only authorized persons have access to those data.

According to Article 58, the implementing acts for AI regulatory sandboxes must include common principles on the following issues to ensure uniformity across the Union:

(a) eligibility and selection criteria for participation in the AI regulatory sandbox;
(b) procedures for the application, participation, monitoring, exiting from and termination of the AI regulatory sandbox, including the sandbox plan and the exit report;
(c) the terms and conditions applicable to the participants.

According to Article 11(1) of the EU AI Act, the technical documentation for an AI system must include the following information:

1. A general description of the AI system, including:
   (a) its intended purpose, the name of the provider, and the version of the system reflecting its relation to previous versions;
   (b) how the AI system interacts with, or can be used to interact with, hardware or software, including with other AI systems, that are not part of the AI system itself, where applicable;
   (c) the versions of relevant software or firmware, and any requirements related to version updates;
   (d) the description of all the forms in which the AI system is placed on the market or put into service, such as software packages embedded into hardware, downloads, or APIs.

Therefore, as a developer of an AI system, you must ensure that your technical documentation includes a clear and comprehensive description of the intended purpose of the system, as well as how it interacts with other hardware or software systems. You must also provide information on the versions of relevant software or firmware and any requirements related to version updates. Finally, you must describe all the forms in which the AI system is placed on the market or put into service.

According to Article 53(1), point (a) of the EU AI Act, the technical documentation for providers of general-purpose AI models must contain at least the following information:

1. A general description of the general-purpose AI model, including:
   (a) the tasks that the model is intended to perform and the type and nature of AI systems in which it can be integrated;
   (b) the acceptable use policies applicable;
   (c) the date of release and methods of distribution;
   (d) the architecture and number of parameters;
   (e) the modality (e.g. text, image) and format of inputs and outputs;
   (f) the license.

It is important to note that this information should be appropriate to the size and risk profile of the model.

According to the EU AI Act, for the purpose of testing in real world conditions outside AI regulatory sandboxes, freely-given informed consent shall be obtained from the subjects of testing prior to their participation in such testing and after their having been duly informed with concise, clear, relevant, and understandable information regarding:

1. The nature and objectives of the testing in real world conditions and the possible inconvenience that may be linked to their participation;
2. The conditions under which the testing in real world conditions is to be conducted, including the expected duration of the subject or subjects' participation;
3. Their rights, and the guarantees regarding their participation, in particular their right to refuse to participate in, and the right to withdraw from, testing in real world conditions at any time without any resulting detriment and without having to provide any justification.

This information must be provided to the subjects in a concise, clear, relevant, and understandable manner.

According to Article 68(3) of the EU AI Act, the scientific panel will advise and support the AI Office in the following tasks:

(a) supporting the implementation and enforcement of the regulation as regards general-purpose AI models and systems, in particular by:

(i) alerting the AI Office of possible systemic risks at Union level of general-purpose AI models, in accordance with Article 90;
(ii) contributing to the development of tools and methodologies for evaluating capabilities of general-purpose AI models and systems, including through benchmarks;

(b) supporting the work of market surveillance authorities, at their request;
(c) supporting cross-border market surveillance activities as referred to in Article 74(11), without prejudice to the powers of market surveillance authorities;
(d) supporting the AI Office in carrying out its duties in the context of the Union safeguard procedure pursuant to Article 81.

It is important to note that the scientific panel will perform these tasks with impartiality and objectivity, and will ensure the confidentiality of information and data obtained in carrying out their tasks and activities. They will neither seek nor take instructions from anyone when exercising their tasks under paragraph 3.

When deciding whether to impose an administrative fine on a Union institution, body, office, or agency in the context of an infringement, all relevant circumstances of the specific situation shall be taken into account, and due regard shall be given to the following factors:

(a) the nature, gravity, and duration of the infringement and its consequences, taking into account the purpose of the AI system concerned, as well as, where appropriate, the number of affected persons and the level of damage suffered by them;

(b) the degree of responsibility of the Union institution, body, office, or agency, taking into account technical and organizational measures implemented by them;

(c) any action taken by the Union institution, body, office, or agency to mitigate the damage suffered by affected persons;

(d) the degree of cooperation with the European Data Protection Supervisor in order to remedy the infringement and mitigate the possible adverse effects of the infringement, including compliance with any of the measures previously ordered by the European Data Protection Supervisor against the Union institution, body, office, or agency concerned with regard to the same subject matter;

(e) any similar previous infringements by the Union institution, body, office, or agency;

(f) the manner in which the infringement became known to the European Data Protection Supervisor, in particular whether, and if so to what extent, the Union institution, body, office, or agency notified the infringement;

(g) the annual budget of the Union institution, body, office, or agency.

Any action taken by the Union institution, body, office, or agency to mitigate the harm suffered by affected persons is also considered. The degree of cooperation with the European Data Protection Supervisor and any similar previous infringements by the Union institution, body, office, or agency are also taken into account.

According to Article 83 of the EU AI Act, the following factors may be taken into account when determining administrative fines for infringements:

1. The nature, gravity, and duration of the infringement;
2. The intentional or negligent character of the infringement;
3. Any action taken by the responsible person to mitigate the damage suffered by data subjects;
4. The degree of responsibility of the responsible person, taking into account technical and organizational measures implemented by them;
5. Any relevant previous infringements by the responsible person;
6. The degree of cooperation with the supervisory authority in order to remedy the infringement and mitigate the possible adverse effects of the infringement;
7. The categories of personal data affected by the infringement;
8. The manner in which the infringement became known to the supervisory authority, in particular whether, and if so to what extent, the responsible person notified the infringement;
9. The extent to which the responsible person has complied with orders or decisions issued by the supervisory authority;
10. Any other aggravating or mitigating factor applicable to the circumstances of the case, such as financial benefits gained, or losses avoided, directly or indirectly, from the infringement.

According to Article 47 of the EU AI Act, the EU declaration of conformity must include the following details:

1. The name and address of the provider of the AI system;
2. The identification of the AI system, including the trade name and model, and any relevant version or serial number;
3. A statement that the AI system conforms to the requirements of the EU AI Act;
4. The date of the declaration;
5. The identity and signature of the person authorized to sign the declaration on behalf of the provider;
6. Any relevant information necessary for the identification of the AI system, including any relevant technical documentation, test reports, or other supporting evidence;
7. Any relevant information necessary for the safe and effective use of the AI system, including instructions for use, warnings, and precautions;
8. Any relevant information necessary for the maintenance and repair of the AI system, including information on spare parts and service providers;
9. Any relevant information necessary for the disposal of the AI system, including information on the environmentally sound disposal of the AI system and its components.

These details must be provided in a clear and concise manner, and in an official language of the Member State where the AI system is placed on the market or put into service.

According to the EU AI Act, when adopting delegated acts concerning safety components of Artificial Intelligence systems, the following factors must be taken into account:

1. The state of the art in AI technology and its foreseeable evolution;
2. The risks associated with the intended use of the AI system, including the severity and likelihood of harm to individuals, the environment, and society as a whole;
3. The principles of safety and transparency, including the need for human oversight and control, and the ability to explain the AI system's decisions and actions;
4. The need to ensure that the AI system is designed and developed in a way that minimizes risks and maximizes benefits;
5. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate testing, verification, and validation procedures;
6. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate monitoring and reporting requirements;
7. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate governance and accountability mechanisms;
8. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate data protection and privacy safeguards;
9. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate cybersecurity measures;
10. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate ethical and societal considerations, including the protection of fundamental rights and non-discrimination.

Article 64 of the EU AI Act outlines the role of the AI Office. According to this article, the AI Office will be established as a Union body with legal personality. Its main role will be to support the Commission in the implementation of the EU AI Act and to ensure its consistent application across the EU. 

The specific tasks of the AI Office include:

(a) providing advice and expertise to the Commission, Member States, and other stakeholders on matters related to the implementation and application of the EU AI Act;

(b) supporting the development of technical standards and guidelines for the conformity assessment of AI systems;

(c) maintaining a publicly accessible database of high-risk AI systems that have been placed on the market or put into service in the EU;

(d) facilitating cooperation and exchange of information between Member States and with the Commission on matters related to the implementation and application of the EU AI Act;

(e) promoting the development of best practices and ethical guidelines for the development and use of AI systems;

(f) supporting the Commission in the development of AI literacy and public awareness initiatives;

(g) carrying out any other tasks assigned to it by the Commission in relation to the implementation and application of the EU AI Act.

According to Article 29 of the EU AI Act, conformity assessment bodies must submit the following information with their application for notification:

1. The name and address of the conformity assessment body and the identification number assigned to it by the national accreditation body;

2. The name and address of the conformity assessment body's legal representative, if any, established in the Union;

3. The scope of the conformity assessment activities for which the conformity assessment body is seeking notification, including the categories of AI systems covered;

4. The list of conformity assessment procedures for which the conformity assessment body is seeking notification, including the categories of AI systems covered;

5. The list of standards and technical specifications used by the conformity assessment body for the conformity assessment procedures for which it is seeking notification;

6. The list of technical experts and assessors available to the conformity assessment body for the conformity assessment procedures for which it is seeking notification;

7. The description of the quality management system of the conformity assessment body, including the procedures for the management of conflicts of interest;

8. The description of the procedures for the notification of changes to the information provided in the application for notification;

9. The description of the procedures for the surveillance of the conformity assessment activities carried out by the conformity assessment body;

10. The description of the procedures for the handling of complaints and appeals related to the conformity assessment activities carried out by the conformity assessment body;

11. The description of the procedures for the withdrawal, suspension or limitation of the notification of the conformity assessment body;

12. The declaration that the conformity assessment body complies with the requirements of this Regulation and the relevant harmonised standards and technical specifications;

13. The declaration that the conformity assessment body has the financial and technical resources necessary for the proper performance of its conformity assessment activities.

The application for notification must also be accompanied by the relevant supporting documentation, such as the quality manual, procedures and records of the conformity assessment body.
